## **STATEMENT OF WORK (SOW)**

The objective is to develop a robust, scalable backend for a project management application that simplifies documentation and communication across all parties involved in real estate projects. The system is designed to enable:

- **Customers** can sign in, create one or more projects, upload media (photos and videos) for work documentation, and engage in real‑time chat with a company assistant for support.
- **Company Admin/Assistants** to receive notifications for every new project and customer communication via project chat. They have full control over project administration, including uploading media, creating and managing to‑do lists, assigning and revoking project access (with permissions defined as full assistant access or read‑only for Realtors), setting project costs, and closing projects.
- **Realtors** (external users) to gain read‑only access to projects. They receive invitations and notifications prompting them to sign in and view project details, ensuring they stay updated without altering any project content.

The backend will expose secure, scalable RESTful (or optionally GraphQL) APIs to support mobile and web clients. It will also integrate real‑time notifications, role‑based access control, and support for third‑party integrations, ensuring all stakeholders remain informed throughout the project lifecycle.

## **2\. Requirements**

### **2.1 Functional Requirements**

- **Authentication & Authorization:**
  - Secure OAuth 2.0–based sign‑in for all users.
  - Role‑based access control for Customers, Company Admin/Assistants, and Realtors.
- **Project Management:**
  - Customers can create, update, and manage multiple projects.
  - Company Admin/Assistants can update project status (e.g., set costs, close projects), create project-specific to‑do lists, and manage access for Realtors.
  - Realtors have read‑only access and receive invites/notifications to view projects.
- **Media Management:**
  - Customers and Admin/Assistants can upload photos and videos.
  - Media files are stored in scalable cloud storage.
  - Automatic tagging with metadata (timestamp, location, project ID, user ID).
- **Communication & Notifications:**
  - Integrated project chat: Customers can interact with the company assistant.
  - Admin/Assistants receive notifications for new projects and incoming customer messages.
  - Realtors receive notifications and invitation alerts for access to projects.
- **Task & Workflow Management:**
  - Company Admin/Assistants can create and manage project to‑do lists.
  - Tasks can be assigned, marked complete, and linked to specific projects.
- **Reporting & Analytics:**
  - Generate detailed project reports (PDF or AI‑generated summaries) combining media, annotations, and workflow data.
  - Dashboards to visualize project progress, cost tracking, and team activity.
- **APIs & Integrations:**
  - Expose RESTful/GraphQL APIs for interaction with mobile/web clients.
  - Support webhook notifications and integration with third‑party systems (e.g., CRM, accounting, scheduling tools).

### **2.2 Non-Functional Requirements**

- **Scalability:**
  - Design to support high volumes of concurrent uploads and user interactions.
  - Use of horizontal scaling and microservices to ensure modular growth.
- **Performance:**
  - Low latency for media retrieval and real‑time notifications.
  - Optimized database queries and caching strategies for fast access to project data.
- **Security:**
  - End‑to‑end encryption for data in transit and at rest.
  - Regular audits and compliance with data protection regulations.
- **Reliability & Availability:**
  - High availability through load balancing, redundancy, and failover mechanisms.
  - Disaster recovery plans to protect against data loss.
- **Maintainability & Extensibility:**
  - Modular service design that facilitates future feature additions.
  - Comprehensive logging and monitoring for proactive issue resolution.

## **3\. Stakeholders**

- **Customer:**
  - Primary user who, after signing in, can create one or more projects, upload media (photos/videos) to document project progress, and initiate chat sessions with the company assistant for support.
- **Company Admin/Assistant:**
  - In‑house support personnel who receive notifications for every new project and customer communication. They can upload media, manage a project to‑do list, assign or remove access (granting either full assistant access or read‑only access) to Realtors, set project cost parameters, and close projects once completed.
- **Realtor:**
  - External users who have read‑only access to projects. They receive invites and notifications prompting them to sign in and view project details, ensuring they remain informed about the project’s status without the ability to modify content.

## **4\. Core Features**

- **Media Management:**
  - **Capture & Upload:** Seamless media capture from mobile or web; auto‑attachment of metadata.
  - **Cloud Storage:** Scalable storage solution ensuring reliable access and backup.
- **Project & Workflow Management:**
  - **Project Creation & Management:** Customers can initiate projects; Admin/Assistants can update project details, assign tasks, set costs, and close projects.
  - **Access Control:** Granular role‑based permissions allowing Admin/Assistants to manage Realtor access.
  - **Task Lists:** Ability for Admin/Assistants to create and manage projects‑specific to‑do lists.
- **Communication & Notifications:**
  - **In-App Chat:** Real‑time chat functionality connecting Customers and Company Admin/Assistants.
  - **Notification System:** Immediate alerts for new projects, messages, and project access changes.
- **Reporting & Analytics:**
  - **Report Generation:** Customizable project reports integrating media, annotations, and workflow data.
  - **Dashboards:** Visual dashboards for tracking project progress, costs, and team performance.
- **APIs & Integrations:**
  - **Secure API Endpoints:** RESTful or GraphQL APIs for client integration.
  - **Webhooks & Third‑Party Integrations:** Real‑time event notifications and connectivity with external systems.

## **5\. User Flows**

### 5.1 Customer Workflow

1. **Login & Dashboard:**
    - The customer logs in via OAuth 2.0, receiving a secure session.
    - The dashboard displays existing projects and options to create a new project or access chats.
2. **Project Creation & Media Upload:**
    - The customer creates a new project by entering details (project name, location, etc.).
    - After project creation, the customer uploads media (photos/videos) which are stored with associated metadata.
    - The system acknowledges media upload and updates the project feed in real time.
3. **Chat with Company Assistant:**
    - Within the project view, the customer can initiate a chat with the company assistant.
    - Chat messages are stored and trigger notifications to the Company Admin/Assistant.

### 5.2 Company Admin/Assistant Workflow

1. **Dashboard & Notifications:**
    - Upon login, the admin/assistant views a dashboard with real-time notifications for new projects and incoming customer chats.
2. **Project Management & Task Assignment:**
    - The admin reviews new projects, uploads supplemental media if needed, and creates a to‑do list for each project.
    - They assign or revoke access for Realtors, setting permissions as either full assistant (if needed for collaboration) or read‑only.
    - The admin sets project cost details and eventually closes projects once work is complete.
3. **Communication Oversight:**
    - The admin monitors project chat communications, responding to queries and ensuring customer needs are met.
    - All interactions trigger notifications to maintain a proactive support system.

### **5.3 Realtor Workflow**

1. **Invitation & Sign In:**
    - Realtors receive an email or in‑app invitation with a secure link to sign in.
    - Upon login, they gain read‑only access to assigned projects.
2. **Project Viewing & Notifications:**
    - Realtors navigate through their dashboard to view project details, media, and updates.
    - They receive notifications for any updates or when new projects are assigned.
    - Realtors can review the documentation but cannot edit or upload media.

## 6\. High-level Architecture

This architecture leverages the strengths of each technology:

**ENCORE.dev** provides a scalable, non-blocking backend capable of handling real-time communication and complex business logic.

**Clerk** simplifies authentication, session management, and security.

**Neon Database** ensures high availability and scalability for structured data with minimal operational overhead.

- **Mobile Client (React Native):**
  - Provides a cross‑platform mobile application for Customers, Company Admin/Assistants, and Realtors.
  - Integrates with Clerk’s SDK to handle secure sign‑in, user session management, and token handling.
  - Communicates with the Node.js backend via HTTPS (RESTful or GraphQL API).
- **Backend Server (Node.js):**
  - Serves as the core business logic layer, implementing RESTful endpoints for project management, media uploads, chat, and notifications.
  - Uses middleware to validate Clerk JWT tokens ensuring that only authenticated requests are processed.
  - Handles real‑time communications (e.g., via WebSockets or similar technologies) for live updates.
  - Leverages an ORM (e.g., Prisma) or a direct PostgreSQL client to interact with Neon Database.
- **Authentication (Clerk):**
  - Manages user registration, sign‑in, multi-factor authentication, and session management.
  - Provides secure JWT tokens that the React Native client sends along with every API request.
  - Offloads a significant portion of the authentication logic, letting the backend focus on business logic.
- **Database (Neon Database):**
  - Acts as the primary data store using a serverless PostgreSQL database.
  - Supports scaling automatically with minimal configuration.
  - Stores structured data such as user profiles, projects, media metadata, chat messages, and to‑do lists.
  - Offers high performance and cost‑efficiency suitable for applications with variable workloads.

## 7\. Detailed integration flow

1. **User Authentication:**
    - **React Native App:** Uses Clerk’s React Native SDK to initiate user authentication.
    - **Clerk:** On successful sign‑in, Clerk returns a JWT token representing the authenticated user.
    - **API Request:** The mobile app includes this token in the Authorization header for each API call.
2. **API Request Processing:**
    - **Node.js Middleware:** A middleware layer verifies the JWT token from Clerk. If valid, it attaches the user’s identity and permissions to the request context.
    - **Business Logic:** The backend processes the request (e.g., creating a new project, uploading media, managing chat) based on the verified user role.
3. **Data Persistence:**
    - **ORM/Database Client:** Node.js communicates with Neon Database to read and write project data, media metadata, task lists, and chat logs.
    - **Neon Database:** As a serverless PostgreSQL instance, it scales automatically to support fluctuating workloads while ensuring data consistency and security.
4. **Real-Time Communication:**
    - **Node.js Real-Time Engine:** For features like live project feeds or chat notifications, the backend can use WebSockets (or libraries like Socket.io) to push updates in real time.
    - **Client Update:** The React Native client subscribes to these updates to provide immediate feedback and an interactive user experience.

## 8\. Deployment & Scalability Considerations

- **Node.js Server:**
  - Can be containerized (using Docker) and deployed on cloud platforms like AWS, Google Cloud, or Encore.
  - Implements load balancing and auto-scaling strategies to handle spikes in API requests.
  - Uses stateless design principles so that multiple instances can run concurrently.
- **Neon Database:**
  - As a serverless PostgreSQL provider, Neon handles scaling automatically.
  - Regular backups, replication, and monitoring ensure data durability and high availability.
- **Security & Monitoring:**
  - Use HTTPS for all client-server communication.
  - Integrate with logging and monitoring services (e.g., Prometheus, Grafana, or cloud-native equivalents) to track performance and detect anomalies.
  - Regularly update dependencies and conduct security audits, especially for the authentication layer via Clerk.
